<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-641-920  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 641 920.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Wall Street Journal  July 18 1990 pB4(W) pB4(E) 10 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Japan firms face charge of dumping high-tech screens.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lachica, Eduardo.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>US manufacturers of electronic flat-panel display screens havefiled an anti-dumping complaint against a number of Japanesecompetitors in a last gasp effort for the survival of the USindustry.andP;  The complaint alleges that certain Japanese companiesare selling advanced, electronic display screens in the US at farless than their production costs or home market prices.andP;  TheJapanese companies could be subject to penalty duties ranging from71 percent to 318 percent of their current US prices if thecomplaint is upheld.andP;  The Japanese companies are likely to basetheir defense on the principle of forward-pricing, which canjustify some initial below-cost sales if the producers intend torecover costs over the product's life.andP;  The US Commerce Departmentrequires that costs be recovered within a year.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Japanese CompetitionLaw SuitFlat Panel Displays.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>